Treatment and care vary vastly by country income level ‚Äî in low-income countries fewer than 10% of people with psychosis receive care, compared to more than 50% in high-income nations. 
eMHIC

Government spending on mental health remains low ‚Äî globally the median spend is about 2% of health budgets, with minimal change since 2017. 
Business Standard

Workforce shortages: globally, the median number of mental health workers is only about 13 per 100,000 population, and far lower in poorer countries. 
Tricontinental Institute

The situation is particularly acute among women, youth, and marginalized populations. 
The New Indian Express
+1

Why It Matters

Human impact ‚Äì Mental health conditions are now one of the leading causes of disability worldwide. People with severe mental disorders also face higher risk of early death (10‚Äì20 years earlier) often due to untreated physical diseases. 
World Health Organization
+1

Economic impact ‚Äì Poor mental health reduces workforce participation, increases absenteeism, and drives hidden social costs. The US $1 trillion estimate underlines that investment in mental health is not only a humanitarian imperative but also an economic one. 
Health Policy Watch
+1

Equity & global health goals ‚Äì The disparity between country income levels shows global inequities. The UN‚Äôs Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) include mental health, but current progress is off-track (e.g., target to reduce suicide by ‚Öì by 2030 may only achieve ~12% reduction at current pace). 
www.ndtv.com
+1

<h1>Key Challenges & Underlying Drivers</h1>

Diagnosis and broad definitions
The WHO has adopted a broad definition of ‚Äúmental health conditions‚Äù that includes not only strict diagnoses but also psychosocial disabilities and other states of distress. Some critics argue this broadening may dilute focus on severe illnesses. 
PMC

Treatment gap and system weakness
Many countries lack community-based mental health services. Psychiatric hospitals dominate in some places, but WHO recommends shifting toward community models and integrating mental health into primary care. 
World Health Organization

Stigma, discrimination and rights
People with mental health conditions still face stigma, exclusion, and violations of rights. Many countries‚Äô mental-health laws are not fully aligned with international human-rights standards. 
Business Standard

Workforce and funding shortfalls
A workforce of 13 mental-health workers per 100,000 people may still be sufficient in high-income countries, but in low-income countries the ratio is dramatically lower (sometimes only one psychiatrist per 200,000 people). 
Tricontinental Institute

Changing social and economic pressures
Globalisation, urbanisation, climate change, pandemics, and digital stressors are all creating new risk environments for mental-health problems. While not all captured in the latest data, the burden is rising. 
PMC

Regional and Country-Level Notes

In low / middle-income countries (LMICs), the gap between need and access is especially wide. Less than 10 % of people with psychosis receive care in the poorest countries. 
eMHIC

Women are disproportionately impacted by anxiety, depression and eating disorders, while men more often suffer from substance-use disorders and ADHD. 
Health Policy Watch

Suicide remains a major concern: an estimated 727,000 lives lost in 2021 worldwide. Suicide is the third leading cause of death among 15‚Äì29-year-olds. 
The New Indian Express
+1

For countries like India, the challenges are especially acute: lifetime prevalence estimates around 13.7 %, with 70‚Äì92 % of people with mental health disorders not receiving treatment. 
Business Standard

What Needs to Happen: Recommendations & Actions

Increase funding: Countries must elevate mental health on the health-budget agenda ‚Äî spending must rise above 2 % and reach levels that allow meaningful service coverage.

Integrate mental health into primary care: Services must be brought closer to people, not siloed in specialist or institutional settings. The WHO action plan emphasises community-based care. 
World Health Organization

Develop the workforce: Train more mental-health professionals, expand non-specialist providers (peer workers, community health workers) especially in resource-poor settings.

Legislative reform & rights-based care: Mental-health laws and policies must align with human-rights standards, protect people from institutionalisation or harmful practices, and promote independence. 
Business Standard

Collection of data and research: More robust data systems are needed to map who is receiving care, how effective it is, and where gaps exist.

Address social determinants: Interventions beyond health care ‚Äî poverty, education, employment, stigma ‚Äî must be addressed as part of broader prevention.

Special focus on youth & vulnerable groups: Early-intervention programs focusing on adolescents and young adults can prevent long-term disability.

Global collaboration: Mental health is a global issue requiring shared learning, investment, and support ‚Äî especially for countries with fewer resources.`
